semorg-field-tool-type-parameters: input type=combobox|existing values only|values=Direct Provision,Capacity Building,Knowledge Development,Infrastructure Development,Movement Building,Advocacy
semorg-field-tool-type-help:
• '''Direct Provision''': provide your solutions directly to users as products or services
  • '''Capacity Building''': improve abilities of others to provide your solutions to users
  • '''Knowledge Development''': generate missing data and evidence, test, codify, and share your solutions with others
  • '''Infrastructure Development''': transparency, communication, standards, certifications, awards, incentives
  • '''Movement Building''': awareness, mass mobilisation and action
  • '''Advocacy''': laws, policies, regulations in public and private sectors

semorg-field-stakeholder-name-help: Start with a long-list of players that have a stake in your targeted sytem change. Think about the milestones and who can put these in place, but also look in adjacent systems and check back with the problem tree – who else is affected? Which players do you already engage, which ones not (yet)?
semorg-field-stakeholder-role-help: What role could the stakeholder play? List what valuable asset/capacity a partner can bring to the table.
semorg-field-stakeholder-hook-help: What would hook this stakeholder in? List how you could get that player to join your cause. What's in it for them?
semorg-field-stakeholder-importance-help: Rate this stakeholder's importance relative to your strategic priorities. Who should be your best allies?
semorg-field-smart-network-type-help:
'''Types of Actors''':
  • '''Resource Providers''': providers of financial, human, knowledge, networking, and technological resources, and any brokers or intermediaries that channel these resources to those who want them
  • '''Competitors''': organizations that compete with you for resources, and those that compete to serve the same beneficiaries
  • '''Complementary Organizations and Allies''': players who help you achieve your vision: partners who perform critical steps in your theory of change, players who support the same issue, and those who provide important complementary services
  • '''Beneficiaries and Customers''': clients, patients, customers, and others who benefit from your acitivities, either directly or indirectly
  • '''Opponents and Troublemakers''': these palyers contribute to the problems you are addressing, undermine your ability to achieve your vision, or oppose your efforts politically
  • '''Affected or Influential Bystanders''': this is a catchall category to make you think about players who have no direct impact now, but who are affected by your efforts or who could influence your success
